coming in has changed in some way. So I have two things I kind of want to point you to about this.

00:19:23.959 --> 00:19:31.880
The first is that Vetiver has some of these checks built in. Vetiver uses what we call

00:19:32.599 --> 00:19:39.800
an input data prototype. Basically, let me talk about the shape and the characteristics of the

00:19:39.800 --> 00:19:46.280
input data for the model. Let me record that as metadata, as part of the model, and then we will

00:19:46.280 --> 00:19:53.719
check it whenever we make a prediction and check that was coming in, like, complies with the input

00:19:53.719 --> 00:20:02.760
data prototype. This can also be customized. You can actually make stricter checks or you can turn

00:20:02.760 --> 00:20:07.400
it off if for some reason that's appropriate to you. So the default is a kind of middle road in

00:20:07.400 --> 00:20:13.880
terms of strictness of this getting checked. So basically what happens here is instead of

00:20:14.040 --> 00:20:22.599
finding out some data was missing and you're just getting wrong answers, instead it errors. So you

00:20:22.599 --> 00:20:27.959
immediately know, like you immediately know. The other thing that's going on here is that this is

00:20:27.959 --> 00:20:35.880
kind of a question about model monitoring. And I gave a talk last year at PositConf, like a talk

00:20:35.880 --> 00:20:42.680
that was called Reliable Maintenance of Machine Learning Models. And it walks through the different

00:20:42.760 --> 00:20:48.680
kinds of monitoring you can do. So I would say, like, what kind of checkpoints are we talking

